&gt;From article &lt;1927@edison.GE.COM&gt;, by rja@edison.GE.COM (rja):

&gt; .............................  On the other hand, IBM in Switzerland
&gt; is still under .ibm.com rather than under .CH .   I wish we would have
&gt; the nic folks clarify the exact situation, but I think that institutions
&gt; outside North America _can_ be registered under .EDU, .COM, .ORG, etc.

One net result of registering a European organization under something like
COM or ORG is that this organization will not be reachable through the
standard European gateways. This is certainly OK for European branches of
large multinational companies like IBM, which maintain large internal nets:
for example our mail from "mirsa.inria.fr" (in Valbonne) to
"some.one@dec.com" (also in Valbonne, next door actually) crosses the ocean
twice, because the single recommanded gateway to ``DEC.COM'' lays somewhere
in the USA. But I doubt that many European Universities would be ready to
maintain a private link to the Internet, instead of sharing some regional or
national facility...

Christian Huitema

